<Layout title="Fertility Medications" description="Guide to fertility medications including Clomid, Letrozole, and gonadotropins. Learn about oral and injectable options, costs, success rates, and side effects.">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>Fertility Medications</h1>
			<p>Oral and injectable medications used to induce or enhance ovulation.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>Overview</h2>
		<p>Fertility medications are often the first-line treatment for women who have irregular ovulation or unexplained infertility. These medications work by stimulating the ovaries to produce one or more eggs.</p>

		<h2>Oral Medications</h2>

		<h3>Clomiphene Citrate (Clomid, Serophene)</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p><strong>How it works:</strong> Blocks estrogen receptors in the brain, causing increased FSH production and ovulation.</p>
			<p><strong>Typical protocol:</strong> 50-150mg daily for 5 days, starting on cycle day 3-5.</p>
			<p><strong>Success rates:</strong> 80% will ovulate; 10-12% pregnancy rate per cycle.</p>
			<p><strong>Side effects:</strong> Hot flashes, mood changes, headaches, visual disturbances, ovarian cysts.</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $10-$100 per cycle (generic available).</p>
			<p><strong>Multiple pregnancy risk:</strong> 5-10% twins, &lt;1% higher-order multiples.</p>
		</div>

		<h3>Letrozole (Femara)</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p><strong>How it works:</strong> Aromatase inhibitor that lowers estrogen, triggering FSH release.</p>
			<p><strong>Typical protocol:</strong> 2.5-7.5mg daily for 5 days, starting on cycle day 3-5.</p>
			<p><strong>Success rates:</strong> Similar or slightly better than Clomid, especially for PCOS.</p>
			<p><strong>Side effects:</strong> Fewer side effects than Clomid; fatigue, hot flashes, headache.</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $20-$150 per cycle (generic available).</p>
			<p><strong>Advantages:</strong> Lower multiple pregnancy rate, better endometrial lining.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>Letrozole vs. Clomid (NEJM Study):</strong> A landmark multicenter trial of 750 women with PCOS found letrozole resulted in significantly higher live birth rates (<strong>27.5% vs. 19.1%</strong>) compared to clomiphene. Letrozole is now considered first-line treatment for PCOS.
			<p class="citation" style="margin-bottom:0;">Source: <a href="https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1313517" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Legro RS, et al. NEJM 2014</a></p>
		</div>

		<h2>Injectable Medications (Gonadotropins)</h2>

		<h3>FSH Medications</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p><strong>Brand names:</strong> Follistim, Gonal-F, Bravelle</p>
			<p><strong>How it works:</strong> Directly stimulates the ovaries to produce follicles.</p>
			<p><strong>Typical protocol:</strong> Daily injections for 8-14 days with monitoring.</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $1,500-$6,000+ per cycle depending on dosage.</p>
			<p><strong>Requires:</strong> Frequent ultrasound and blood monitoring.</p>
		</div>

		<h3>hCG Trigger Shots</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p><strong>Brand names:</strong> Ovidrel, Pregnyl, Novarel</p>
			<p><strong>How it works:</strong> Triggers final egg maturation and ovulation.</p>
			<p><strong>Timing:</strong> Ovulation occurs 36-40 hours after injection.</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $50-$200 per injection.</p>
		</div>

		<h3>GnRH Agonists and Antagonists</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p><strong>Brand names:</strong> Lupron (agonist), Ganirelix, Cetrotide (antagonists)</p>
			<p><strong>How it works:</strong> Prevents premature ovulation during IVF cycles.</p>
			<p><strong>Use:</strong> Typically part of IVF protocols, not standalone treatment.</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Medication Protocols</h2>

		<h3>Timed Intercourse</h3>
		<p>Oral medications + monitoring + timed intercourse at home.</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Least invasive approach</li>
			<li>Good first step for unexplained infertility</li>
			<li>Lower cost than IUI or IVF</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Superovulation + IUI</h3>
		<p>Oral or injectable medications + IUI procedure.</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Increases number of eggs available</li>
			<li>Combined with IUI for better sperm delivery</li>
			<li>Higher success rates than timed intercourse</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Monitoring During Treatment</h2>
		<p>Most medication cycles require monitoring to:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Track follicle development</strong> via transvaginal ultrasound</li>
			<li><strong>Measure hormone levels</strong> (estradiol, LH, progesterone)</li>
			<li><strong>Time ovulation</strong> for intercourse or IUI</li>
			<li><strong>Prevent complications</strong> like ovarian hyperstimulation (OHSS)</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="warning-box">
			<strong>Ovarian Hyperstimulation Syndrome (OHSS):</strong> A potential complication of fertility medications where ovaries become swollen and painful. Mild cases are common; severe cases are rare but require medical attention. Risk is higher with injectable medications.
		</div>

